		<pubDate>Sun, 05 May 2013 08:46:10 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5134#comment-955</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-945&quot;&gt;James Clear&lt;/a&gt;.

Great points, James!

When talking about health, the thing that matters in the end is results. And if the results are reached via some sort of placebo effect, I don&#039;t see anything wrong with that.

That is, as long as we understand and accept that it&#039;s a nurturing care, more time with the patients and positive affection that&#039;s working and not some sort of random &quot;chanting&quot; or &quot;calling your guardian angel&quot;.

When we understand this we can move forward and implement the aspects that work and discard what&#039;s not working.

&quot;more time with patients and showing them nurturing care — something that our medical system could use more of.&quot;

That&#039;s a very good point. We are often so obsessed with running everything as a business and forget that for something like health, aiming for highest revenue per hour or maximum clients served per hour is not necessarily the way to go, long term.

Cheers]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-945">James Clear</a>.</p>
<p>Great points, James!</p>
<p>When talking about health, the thing that matters in the end is results. And if the results are reached via some sort of placebo effect, I don&#8217;t see anything wrong with that.</p>
<p>That is, as long as we understand and accept that it&#8217;s a nurturing care, more time with the patients and positive affection that&#8217;s working and not some sort of random &#8220;chanting&#8221; or &#8220;calling your guardian angel&#8221;.</p>
<p>When we understand this we can move forward and implement the aspects that work and discard what&#8217;s not working.</p>
<p>&#8220;more time with patients and showing them nurturing care — something that our medical system could use more of.&#8221;</p>
<p>That&#8217;s a very good point. We are often so obsessed with running everything as a business and forget that for something like health, aiming for highest revenue per hour or maximum clients served per hour is not necessarily the way to go, long term.</p>
<p>Cheers</p>
