		<title>
		By: James Clear		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-954</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[James Clear]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 05 May 2013 07:12:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5134#comment-954</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-953&quot;&gt;Andrew Yeh&lt;/a&gt;.

Andrew -- I think you&#039;re getting at an important point. Whether it be exercise or diet or simply taking an active interest in the patient&#039;s life ... the lack of time for many physicians strips this opportunity away. As you point out, this is one of the burdens that a large society places on healthcare practitioners.

Another important thing to note is that while doctor&#039;s get most of the press, it doesn&#039;t have to come down to the physician. There are plenty of other people in the system &#8212; nurses, physician&#039;s assistants, physical therapists, etc. &#8212; who can provide guidance and training on these topics as well. While doctors are pressed for time, there is no reason we can&#039;t build behavior change into the medical system somewhere.

Regardless, I think your underlying reasoning is on target: smaller and simpler societies have an easier time implementing time intensive changes than large societies do.

Thanks for reading! It&#039;s great to have you sharing your thoughts here.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-953">Andrew Yeh</a>.</p>
<p>Andrew &#8212; I think you&#8217;re getting at an important point. Whether it be exercise or diet or simply taking an active interest in the patient&#8217;s life &#8230; the lack of time for many physicians strips this opportunity away. As you point out, this is one of the burdens that a large society places on healthcare practitioners.</p>
<p>Another important thing to note is that while doctor&#8217;s get most of the press, it doesn&#8217;t have to come down to the physician. There are plenty of other people in the system &mdash; nurses, physician&#8217;s assistants, physical therapists, etc. &mdash; who can provide guidance and training on these topics as well. While doctors are pressed for time, there is no reason we can&#8217;t build behavior change into the medical system somewhere.</p>
<p>Regardless, I think your underlying reasoning is on target: smaller and simpler societies have an easier time implementing time intensive changes than large societies do.</p>
<p>Thanks for reading! It&#8217;s great to have you sharing your thoughts here.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
