		<item>
		<title>
		By: Andrew Yeh		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-953</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Andrew Yeh]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 05 May 2013 05:46:40 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5134#comment-953</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I wonder how society&#039;s attitude towards prescribing action versus prescribing medication differs with regards to societies.

My guess is that the more complicated and large a society (US), the more likely it&#039;ll be that medication is prescribed. And there would be good reasons for doctors to prescribe medication instead of action. There&#039;s less time and energy to devote to each patient in creating a good exercise program, and it&#039;s harder to make sure there&#039;s a follow-up visit which is important for a non-boolean, non-specific treament like action (is he only doing half? does he remember how many to do? when is he doing it?). 

Additionally, exercise programs are entirely under the control of the doctor. If a drug doesn&#039;t work, it&#039;s the drug&#039;s fault. But if an exercise program doesn&#039;t work, it&#039;s the doctor&#039;s fault.

By contrast, in a smaller country like, perhaps, Sweden (as mentioned in an earlier comment), the doctor has more time to figure out exactly what exercise program to assign to a patient and more of a chance to follow up.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I wonder how society&#8217;s attitude towards prescribing action versus prescribing medication differs with regards to societies.</p>
<p>My guess is that the more complicated and large a society (US), the more likely it&#8217;ll be that medication is prescribed. And there would be good reasons for doctors to prescribe medication instead of action. There&#8217;s less time and energy to devote to each patient in creating a good exercise program, and it&#8217;s harder to make sure there&#8217;s a follow-up visit which is important for a non-boolean, non-specific treament like action (is he only doing half? does he remember how many to do? when is he doing it?). </p>
<p>Additionally, exercise programs are entirely under the control of the doctor. If a drug doesn&#8217;t work, it&#8217;s the drug&#8217;s fault. But if an exercise program doesn&#8217;t work, it&#8217;s the doctor&#8217;s fault.</p>
<p>By contrast, in a smaller country like, perhaps, Sweden (as mentioned in an earlier comment), the doctor has more time to figure out exactly what exercise program to assign to a patient and more of a chance to follow up.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
