		<item>
		<title>
		By: James Clear		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-949</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[James Clear]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 04 May 2013 17:16:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5134#comment-949</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-937&quot;&gt;Erinn Clevinger&lt;/a&gt;.

Erinn -- thanks so much for sharing your story and your husband&#039;s experiences. I think they are the perfect complement to what I&#039;m talking about here. 

Two points I want to clarify...

First, I hope I didn&#039;t come across as saying that we should abandon all science-based treatment and medication. I think the best solution is a combination of these methods with the science of behavior change. Not all drugs are as great as they claim to be, but many of them are scientifically proven and I think we should keep using them. Additionally, even when behavior change is a good option I think that pharmaceuticals are a great way to get more immediate short-term results for patients while they work on building better long-term habits.

Secondly, you say that it&#039;s very easy to point to doctors as the problem. I agree with that, but I think it&#039;s just as easy to point to patients as the problem. I hear a lot of physicians (and nurses, physical therapists, etc.) complaining about their patients being non-complaint and not following directions. Rather than patients blaming doctors or doctors blaming patients, I&#039;d like to see more time and energy spent teaching and learning how to make positive long-term changes. When we spend all day tossing blame around, nobody benefits.

What&#039;s important is that no matter what side you fall on, you take responsibility for doing what you can to make healthy changes easier. For my part, I research the science of behavior change and do my best to share practical insights with readers. And if I end up becoming a physician in the near future, then I&#039;ll do my best to share similar insights with my patients. 

Many other people in our audience are doing better than I am -- they are practicing it in their own lives. Kim Bova, who commented above, is a good example of that. Your story about losing weight and taking your health into your own hands is in another great example. (Well done, by the way.)

Long story short, I think we (you, me and doctors like your husband) are all on the same team end of the day. We all want to help people live healthier and get the most out of life.

Thanks for sharing your story and taking the time to read! It&#039;s great to have you in our little community.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://jamesclear.com/actions-instead-of-medications#comment-937">Erinn Clevinger</a>.</p>
<p>Erinn &#8212; thanks so much for sharing your story and your husband&#8217;s experiences. I think they are the perfect complement to what I&#8217;m talking about here. </p>
<p>Two points I want to clarify&#8230;</p>
<p>First, I hope I didn&#8217;t come across as saying that we should abandon all science-based treatment and medication. I think the best solution is a combination of these methods with the science of behavior change. Not all drugs are as great as they claim to be, but many of them are scientifically proven and I think we should keep using them. Additionally, even when behavior change is a good option I think that pharmaceuticals are a great way to get more immediate short-term results for patients while they work on building better long-term habits.</p>
<p>Secondly, you say that it&#8217;s very easy to point to doctors as the problem. I agree with that, but I think it&#8217;s just as easy to point to patients as the problem. I hear a lot of physicians (and nurses, physical therapists, etc.) complaining about their patients being non-complaint and not following directions. Rather than patients blaming doctors or doctors blaming patients, I&#8217;d like to see more time and energy spent teaching and learning how to make positive long-term changes. When we spend all day tossing blame around, nobody benefits.</p>
<p>What&#8217;s important is that no matter what side you fall on, you take responsibility for doing what you can to make healthy changes easier. For my part, I research the science of behavior change and do my best to share practical insights with readers. And if I end up becoming a physician in the near future, then I&#8217;ll do my best to share similar insights with my patients. </p>
<p>Many other people in our audience are doing better than I am &#8212; they are practicing it in their own lives. Kim Bova, who commented above, is a good example of that. Your story about losing weight and taking your health into your own hands is in another great example. (Well done, by the way.)</p>
<p>Long story short, I think we (you, me and doctors like your husband) are all on the same team end of the day. We all want to help people live healthier and get the most out of life.</p>
<p>Thanks for sharing your story and taking the time to read! It&#8217;s great to have you in our little community.</p>
